<font color="#FF0000">VIET VET WIFE TALK</font><br>
<tt>Sun May 25 12:50:04 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I am proud to be the wife of a Viet Vet.<br><br>
There have been hard times and he still goes through periods where he's wildly defensive and I cannot communicate with him.  I can't even say &quot;these are pretty, purple candles&quot; without it turning into a conflict (on his part).<br><br>
Fortunately, he settles down and becomes more normal if I draw his attention to how he is acting.  It may take a couple of days, however, for him to come around.<br><br>
I love him dearly, and go on with my life even when he's out in left field.  This seems to be the best for him, to keep a reasonable home front and let him know when he's being outrageous.  It takes patience, caring and understanding.<br><br>
Anyone considering marrying or having an involvement with a Viet Nam Vet should consider talking with a Vet Center counselor first.  This would help prepare you for what to expect from a relationship with a Vet.  They require much devotion from a strong partner who is aware of who they are; otherwise, it could lead to a very disfunctional relationship that is unsatisfying with regard to intimacy and communication.<br><br>
Many times I go through periods with my husband where I feel I am living alone.  At the same time, he's acting out and causing problems.  It's a good thing that I like being alone, and the good times are worth his episodes.  He is so fun, humerous and energetic.  He cares about people like no other and of course (vet like), would protect those he cares about with his life.<br><br>
Any other wives out there?  I'd love to hear from you.  The vet center had a group of wives who talked together for a while, but has since desolved when the counselor relocated to Oregon.
